14 = 18 | goals14 = 2   \n| years15 = 2008      | clubs15 = [[FC Nizhny Novgorod (2007)|FC Nizhny Novgorod]] | caps15 =  8 | goals15 = 0  \n| years16 = 2008      | clubs16 = [[FC Lukhovitsy]]                                | caps16 = 17 | goals16 = 3  \n| years17 = 2009      | clubs17 = [[FC Gubkin]]                                    | caps17 =  3 | goals17 = 0 \n| pcupdate = \n| ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Yuri Vladimirovich Doroshenko''' ({{lang-ru|\u042e\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0414\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e}}; born 30 August 1980) is a former [[Russia]]n professional [[Association football|football]] player. He also holds [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] citizenship as '''Yuriy Volodymyrovych Doroshenko''' ({{lang-ua|\u042e\u0440\u0456\u0439 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0414\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e}}).\n\n==Club career==\nHe played 3 seasons in the [[Russian Football National League]] for [[FC Arsenal Tula]], [[FC KAMAZ Naberezhnye Chelny]] and [[FC Oryol]].\n\n==External links==\n* {{FootballFacts.ru|16747-doroshenko-yurij-vladimirovich}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doroshenko, Yuri}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian emigrants to Russia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:FC Dynamo-2 Kyiv players]]\n[[Category:FC Dynamo-3 Kyiv players]]\n[[Category:PFC Sumy players]]\n[[Category:FC Obolon-Brovar Kyiv players]]\n[[Category:FC Obolon-2 Kyiv players]]\n[[Category:FC Arsenal Tula players]]\n[[Category:FC Metallurg Lipetsk players]]\n[[Category:FC Khimik-Arsenal players]]\n[[Category:FC KAMAZ Naberezhnye Chelny players]]\n[[Category:FC Oryol players]]\n[[Category:FC Volga Nizhny Novgorod players]]\n[[Category:FC Nizhny Novgorod players]]\n[[Category:FC Lukhovitsy players]]\n\n\n{{Russia-footy-forward-1980s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update FootballFacts.ru template, misc formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuri_Doroshenko"}
{"title_page": "David Nabarro", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = David Nabarro\n| image               = David Nabarro April 2016 (26106492653) (cropped).jpg\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1949|8|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[London]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| education           = [[Oundle School]], [[University of Oxford]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of Science|MS]], [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|MBBS]])}}<br>[[University of London]] {{small|([[Master of Science|MS]])}}\n| honorific_suffix    = [[Commander of the Order of British Empire| CBE]]\n}}\n'''David Nabarro''' (born 26 August 1949) is a medical doctor, international civil servant and diplomat, who served as special adviser to the [[United Nations]] (UN) [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary-General]] on the [[Sustainable Development Goals|2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development]] and Climate Change. He also led the UN's response to the [[cholera]] epidemic in [[Haiti]] and previously served as the [[Diplomatic rank|special envoy]] on [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=24|title=David Nabarro - David Nabarro's Career History|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> In September 2016, Nabarro was nominated by the UK to stand for the post of director-general (DG) of the [[World Health Organization|World Health Organization (WHO)]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://healthmedia.blog.gov.uk/2016/10/21/the-uk-backs-dr-david-nabarro-in-his-bid-to-lead-the-world-health-organisation/|title=The UK backs Dr David Nabarro in his bid to lead the World Health Organisation {{!}} Department of Health Media Centre|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> In 2018 he was appointed Professor at the [[UCL Institute for Global Health]] and became then appointed as Co-Director in 2019 joining [[Ara Darzi, Baron Darzi of Denham]]. On 21 February 2020, he was appointed as one of six Special Envoys to the World Health Organization (WHO) Director-General Special Envoy to respond to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19-on-21-february-2020|title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 on 21 February 2020|website=www.who.int|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>. \n\n== Early life and education ==\nNabarro is the son of the late Sir John David Nunes Nabarro \u2013 formerly consultant endocrinologist at [[University College Hospital]] (UCH) and [[Middlesex Hospital]], [[London]].\n\nHe attended [[Oundle School]] in [[Northamptonshire]], leaving in the summer of 1966. \n\nIn a gap year between school and university, Nabarro was a community service volunteer. He spent a year as the organiser of Youth Action, York. A [[BBC]] television documentary was made about his volunteer work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/cace5df451044a1a90f17a7ec91bd47c|title=THE YOUNGER GENERATION - BBC One London - 12 November 1967 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nNabarro studied at the [[University of Oxford]] and the [[University of London]], and qualified as a physician in 1973. He is a member of the [[Faculty of Public Health]] (FPH) and the [[Royal College of Physicians]] by distinction (where he is also a [[Fellow of the Royal College of Physicians|Fellow]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=23|title=David Nabarro - David Nabarro's Education|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Early career ===\n\nNabarro worked as a medical officer in North Iraq for [[Save the Children]], before joining the [[United Kingdom]]'s (UK) [[National Health Service]] (NHS) for a short time. From 1976 to 1978, Nabarro worked as District Child Health Officer in [[Dhankuta]] District, [[Nepal]]. Later, he moved to the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine|London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine]], and in 1982, he became Regional Manager for the [[Save the Children Fund]] in [[South Asia]], based in the region. In 1985 he joined the [[University of Liverpool]] Medical School as senior lecturer in International Community Health.\n\nHe moved to the Overseas Development Administration (now the [[Department for International Development]]) as a strategic adviser for health and population in [[East Africa]], based in [[Nairobi]], in 1989.\n\nNabarro later took up the post of chief health and population adviser at the Overseas Development Administration (London office) in 1990, and moved on to become director of human development (as well as chief health adviser) in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=24|title=David Nabarro \u2013 David Nabarro's Career History|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n===World Health Organization, 1999\u20132005===\n\nNabarro joined the WHO in January 1999, as project manager of [[Roll Back Malaria (RBM) Partnership|Roll Back Malaria]], then moved to the Office of the DG as executive director in March 2000. In this capacity, he worked with DG [[Gro Harlem Brundtland]] for two years on a variety of issues, including the Commission on Macroeconomics and Health, Health Systems Assessments and the creation of the [[The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria|Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria]].\n\nNabarro transferred to the Sustainable Development and Healthy Environments cluster in 2003 and was appointed representative of the DG for health action in crises in July 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=24|title=David Nabarro - David Nabarro's Career History|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nNabarro was stationed in the [[Canal Hotel]] in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]], when it was [[Canal Hotel Bombing|bombed]] on the afternoon of 19 August 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2003/statment_nabarro/en/|title=WHO {{!}} Senior WHO official, Dr David Nabarro, describes his experience in the UN bombing|website=www.who.int|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> The blast targeted the UN, which had used the hotel as its headquarters in Iraq since 1991.\n\nHe has also coordinated support for health aspects of crisis response operations in [[Darfur]], [[Sudan]], and in countries affected by the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and Tsunami]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/about/who_reform/emergency-capacities/advisory-group/david-nabarro/en/|title=David Nabarro|website=World Health Organization|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== UN System senior coordinator for avian and human influenza (assistant secretary-general), September 2005 \u2013 2014 ===\n\nIn September 2005, Nabarro was seconded from [[World Health Organization|WHO]] and appointed senior UN system coordinator for [[Avian influenza|avian]] and human [[influenza]] by secretary-general of the UN [[Kofi Annan]] to ensure that the UN system makes an effective and coordinated contribution to the global effort to control the epidemic of avian influenza (also known as 'bird flu').<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2005/pr45/en/|title=WHO {{!}} WHO expert to work with the UN system on avian and human influenza|website=www.who.int|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Coordinator of the High-Level Task Force on Global Food Security (HLTF), April 2008 \u2013 April 2014 ===\n\nIn January 2009, Nabarro took on the responsibility of coordinating the UN system's [https://www.un.org/en/issues/food/taskforce/index.shtml High-Level Task Force on Global Food Security (HLTF)].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/issues/food/taskforce/establishing.shtml|title=High Level Task Force on Global Food and Nutrition Security (HLTF)|website=www.un.org|language=EN|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> The HLTF brought together 23 different organizations, funds, programs and other entities from within the UN family, as well as the [[Bretton Woods Institutions]], the [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO), and the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/issues/food/taskforce/updatedmembership.shtml|title=High Level Task Force on Global Food and Nutrition Security (HLTF)|website=www.un.org|language=EN|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> and tasked them with establishing a common strategy for addressing food and nutrition insecurity in a more sustainable, coordinated and comprehensive way. Nabarro left the HLTF coordinator position in 2014 and was succeeded by Giuseppe Fantozzi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/issues/food/taskforce/establishing.shtml|title=High Level Task Force on Global Food and Nutrition Security (HLTF)|website=www.un.org|language=EN|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Coordinator of the Scaling Up Nutrition movement, September 2010 \u2013 September 2015 ===\n\nIn September 2010, Nabarro was appointed coordinator of the [http://scalingupnutrition.org/ Scaling Up Nutrition (SUN) Movement].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scalingupnutrition.org/sun-supporters/sun-movement-coordinator/|title=SUN Movement Coordinator|website=scalingupnutrition.org|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> SUN brings together government officials, civil society, the UN, donors, businesses and researchers in a collective effort to improve nutrition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scalingupnutrition.org/about-sun/the-vision-and-principles-of-sun/|title=The vision and principles of SUN|website=scalingupnutrition.org|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Chair of the Advisory Group on Reform of the World Health Organization\u2019s Work in Outbreaks and Emergencies with Health and Humanitarian Consequences., July 2015 \u2013 January 2016 ===\n\nNabarro was responsible for leading a high-level advisory group to guide reform of WHO's response to outbreaks and emergencies, prepare reports based on the group's recommendations and advise on the manner of their implementation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=24|title=David Nabarro - David Nabarro's Career History|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Head of UN's response to cholera in Haiti, summer 2016 \u2013 summer 2017 ===\nIn 2016 Nabarro was tapped to lead the UN's response to Haiti's cholera epidemic. Cholera has killed more than 10,000 Haitians since the disease was introduced by UN peacekeepers in 2010<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/01/world/americas/united-nations-apology-haiti-cholera.html|title=U.N. Apologizes for Role in Haiti\u2019s 2010 Cholera Outbreak|last=Sengupta|first=Somini|date=2016-12-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-06-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>. After UN Secretary General Ban Ki-Moon issued a long overdue apology for the UN's \"role\" in the epidemic, Nabarro oversaw efforts to raise $400 million from UN member states to fund the Secretary General's proposed \"New Approach\" to cholera in Haiti<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/01/world/americas/united-nations-apology-haiti-cholera.html|title=U.N. Apologizes for Role in Haiti\u2019s 2010 Cholera Outbreak|last=Sengupta|first=Somini|date=2016-12-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-06-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>. Nabarro was the second UN appointee to work on the cholera crisis in Haiti. Pedro Modrano Rojas previously served as a senior coordinator for the cholera effort, but left at the end of an 18-month term, stating that he was disappointed by the international community's \"failure to acknowledge the fact that we have in Haiti the largest epidemic in the western hemisphere.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/haiti/article105003956.html|title=British doctor who tackled Ebola now leads fight against cholera in Haiti|access-date=2016-11-23|newspaper=miamiherald}}</ref> Nabarro's efforts were no more successful\u2014as a result of a lack of support from the UN Secretary General and from member states, Nabarro was only been able to raise $2.7 million of the promised $400 million before being replaced by [[Josette Sheeran]]\u2014though Sheeran will face the same obstacles as Nabarro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/haiti/article157148964.html|title=With little money to combat cholera in Haiti, U.N. names new fundraising chief|work=miamiherald|access-date=2017-06-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Special representative of the United Nations Secretary-General for food security and nutrition, November 2009-June 2017 ===\n[[File:Mr. David Nabarro, Special Representative on Food Security and Nutrition, UN High-level Task Force on the Global Food Security Crisis (6139808071).jpg|thumb|Nabarro addresses global food security crisis at Global Commodities Forum, [[United Nations Conference on Trade and Development]]]]\n\nIn November 2009 UN Secretary-General [[Ban Ki-moon]] appointed Nabarro as [[Diplomatic rank|special representative]] on food security and nutrition. As special representative, Nabarro's role is to:\n* Align UN system action on people's food security, livelihood resilience and sustainable agriculture in the face of changing climates\n* Support functioning of the [[Committee on World Food Security]] \n* Oversee UN Secretary-General's [https://www.un.org/zerohunger/ Zero Hunger Challenge].\n\n=== Special adviser to the United Nations Secretary-General on the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development and Climate Change, January 2016\u2013June 2017 ===\n\nIn January 2016, Nabarro was appointed special adviser on the [[Sustainable Development Goals|2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development]] by then UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon.\n\nOne of Nabarro's responsibilities in this role were to lead the UN's response to the cholera epidemic its peacekeepers sparked in Haiti in October 2010 when untreated, infected sewage from a UN base was deposited in the country's main river system. As of August 2016, at least 10,000 people have died and more than 800,000 have been sickened in the ongoing epidemic.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-37126747|title=UN admits role in Haiti's deadly cholera outbreak|date=2016-08-19|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Special envoy of the United Nations Secretary-General on Ebola, August 2014 \u2013 December 2015 ===\n[[File:Dr. David Nabarro, UN Secretary-General's Special Envoy on Ebola speaks at World Organisation for Animal Health.jpg|thumb|David Nabarro speaks at [[World Organization for Animal Health]]]]\n\nIn August 2014, Nabarro was designated as special envoy of the UN Secretary-General on Ebola, with the responsibility for ensuring that the UN system makes an effective and coordinated contribution to the global effort to control the outbreak of Ebola.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ebolaresponse.un.org/special-envoy-ebola|title=Special Envoy on Ebola|date=2014-11-27|newspaper=Global Ebola Response|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> The epidemic is believed to have begun in December 2013 with the death of a 2-year-old boy in a remote area of Guinea, but was not recognized until March 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://who.int/csr/disease/ebola/one-year-report/virus-origin/en/|title=WHO {{!}} Origins of the 2014 Ebola epidemic|website=who.int|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> For several months the epidemic was spreading. This is something that public health experts in the affected locations, such as [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|Medecins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]] (Doctors Without Borders), claimed was due to a deeply flawed and delayed response by health and government officials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/3753684/ebola-medecins-sans-frontiers-west-africa-world-health-organization-slow-response-cost-lives/|title=Slow Response to Ebola Outbreak 'Cost Thousands of Lives'|last=Regan|first=Helen|website=TIME.com|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview later in 2015, once Ebola had largely been brought under control, Nabarro said that when he started working on Ebola in 2014, he \"was aware that we were in the middle of a disease outbreak of enormous proportions. The number of people getting sick was doubling every week. Facilities were completely overloaded. Communities were in a state of despair.\" He added that the international community had learned important lessons from the epidemic: \"The world is going to be different as a result of this Ebola outbreak, much more confident, much more assured, and much, much more capable to ensure the well-being of its citizens.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/features/2015/ebola-then-now-nabarro/en/|title=Ebola Then and Now - David Nabarro|website=World Health Organization|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Candidate for WHO Director-General September 2016  \u2013 May 2017 ===\n\nAn article co-authored by the UK's [[chief medical officer]], [[Sally Davies (doctor)|Sally Davies]], was published in ''[[The Lancet]]''. It outlined the criteria that the next DG of the WHO must fulfill.\n\nNabarro was one of six candidates put forward by their individual governments to succeed WHO DG [[Margaret Chan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2016/election-process-who-director-general/en/|title=Election process for the new WHO Director-General|website=World Health Organization|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nNabarro outlined his four priorities as follows:\n\n# Alignment with the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs)\n# Transforming the WHO to respond to outbreaks and health emergencies\n# Trusted engagement with Member States\n# Advancing people-centred health policies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=29|title=David Nabarro - 4 Priorities|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nOn Tuesday 23 May, at the 70th World Health Assembly, Nabarro came second in the race to become the next director general, receiving 50 votes to [[Tedros Adhanom|Dr Tedros Adhanom]]'s 133 in the third and final round of voting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.9and10news.com/story/35495135/the-latest-pakistani-doctor-eliminated-in-who-leader-vote |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-05-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523170003/http://www.9and10news.com/story/35495135/the-latest-pakistani-doctor-eliminated-in-who-leader-vote |archivedate=2017-05-23 }}</ref>\n\n=== Additional positions ===\n* Member of the board of directors, [[Medicines for Malaria Venture]] (MVV), 1999\u20132001<ref>http://www.mmv.org/sites/default/files/uploads/docs/publications/MMV_10th_Anniversary_Book_5.pdf</ref>\n* Member of the WHO Commission on Ending Childhood Obesity (2016), 2013\u20132014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/end-childhood-obesity/about/bios/david-nabarro/en/|title=WHO {{!}} Biographies of the Commissioners|website=www.who.int|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition and awards ==\n*'''World Food Prize 2018''' (dubbed Nobel Prize for Agriculture): Awarded together with [[Lawrence Haddad]] for their individual and complementary global leadership in elevating maternal and child undernutrition to a central issue within the [[food security]] and development dialogue at national and international levels<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfoodprize.org/en/laureates/2018_laureates/|title=2018 Haddad and Nabarro - The World Food Prize - Improving the Quality, Quantity and Availability of Food in the World|last=globalreach.com|first=Global Reach Internet Productions, LLC-Ames, IA-|website=www.worldfoodprize.org|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>. They have been cutting the number of stunted children in the world by 10 million by lobbying governments and donors to improve [[nutrition]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-global-agriculture-nutrition-analysis-idUSKCN1OR03M|title=From obese to starving, nutrition crisis prompts SOS call for new...|date=2018-12-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2018-12-30|language=en}}</ref>.\n*'''Helen Keller Humanitarian Award:''' Awarded for work on positioning [[malnutrition]] within the development dialogue and for ensuring an effective response to [[Ebolavirus|Ebola]], 2015\n* '''Sight and Life Nutrition Leadership Award (together with the Scaling Up Nutrition Movement):''' For work in [[Catalysis|catalysing]] sustainable change in global nutrition, 2012\n* '''Distinguished Service Award from Health Policy Institute, Kansas University of Medicine & Biosciences:''' For outstanding Health Policy Leadership, 2008\n* '''[[CBE]]:''' Awarded for work on international public health, 1992.\n\n==Personal life==\nNabarro has three older children with his former partner, [[Oxfordshire]] GP Susanna Belle Graham-Jones: Thomas (Tom) Adam Nabarro (1984), Oliver Mark Nabarro (1986) and Polly Frances Graham-Jones Nabarro (1988).{{cn|date=February 2017}} David married Gillian Holmes in 2002, in Coppet, near Geneva, and they have two children: Josephine Mari Holmes Nabarro (1997) and Lucas John Nabarro (2000).{{cn|date=February 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://archive.davidnabarro.info/whodg/en/}}\n* {{C-SPAN|David Nabarro}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nabarro, David}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Academics of the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oundle School]]\n[[Category:British public health doctors]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:British officials of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:United Nations operations in Iraq]]\n[[Category:World Health Organization officials]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = David Nabarro\n| image               = David Nabarro April 2016 (26106492653) (cropped).jpg\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1949|8|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[London]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| education           = [[Oundle School]], [[University of Oxford]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of Science|MS]], [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|MBBS]])}}<br>[[University of London]] {{small|([[Master of Science|MS]])}}\n| honorific_suffix    = [[Commander of the Order of British Empire| CBE]]\n}}\n'''David Nabarro''' (born 26 August 1949) is a medical doctor, international civil servant and diplomat, who served as special adviser to the [[United Nations]] (UN) [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary-General]] on the [[Sustainable Development Goals|2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development]] and Climate Change. He also led the UN's response to the [[cholera]] epidemic in [[Haiti]] and previously served as the [[Diplomatic rank|special envoy]] on [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=24|title=David Nabarro - David Nabarro's Career History|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Nabarro was nominated by the UK to stand for the post of director-general (DG) of the [[World Health Organization|World Health Organization (WHO)]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://healthmedia.blog.gov.uk/2016/10/21/the-uk-backs-dr-david-nabarro-in-his-bid-to-lead-the-world-health-organisation/|title=The UK backs Dr David Nabarro in his bid to lead the World Health Organisation {{!}} Department of Health Media Centre|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nNabarro is the son of the late Sir John David Nunes Nabarro \u2013 formerly consultant endocrinologist at [[University College Hospital]] (UCH) and [[Middlesex Hospital]], [[London]].\n\nHe attended [[Oundle School]] in [[Northamptonshire]], leaving in the summer of 1966. \n\nIn a gap year between school and university, Nabarro was a community service volunteer. He spent a year as the organiser of Youth Action, York. A [[BBC]] television documentary was made about his volunteer work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/cace5df451044a1a90f17a7ec91bd47c|title=THE YOUNGER GENERATION - BBC One London - 12 November 1967 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nNabarro studied at the [[University of Oxford]] and the [[University of London]], and qualified as a physician in 1973. He is a member of the [[Faculty of Public Health]] (FPH) and the [[Royal College of Physicians]] by distinction (where he is also a [[Fellow of the Royal College of Physicians|Fellow]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=23|title=David Nabarro - David Nabarro's Education|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Early career ===\n\nNabarro worked as a medical officer in North Iraq for [[Save the Children]], before joining the [[United Kingdom]]'s (UK) [[National Health Service]] (NHS) for a short time. From 1976 to 1978, Nabarro worked as District Child Health Officer in [[Dhankuta]] District, [[Nepal]]. Later, he moved to the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine|London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine]], and in 1982, he became Regional Manager for the [[Save the Children Fund]] in [[South Asia]], based in the region. In 1985 he joined the [[University of Liverpool]] Medical School as senior lecturer in International Community Health.\n\nHe moved to the Overseas Development Administration (now the [[Department for International Development]]) as a strategic adviser for health and population in [[East Africa]], based in [[Nairobi]], in 1989.\n\nNabarro later took up the post of chief health and population adviser at the Overseas Development Administration (London office) in 1990, and moved on to become director of human development (as well as chief health adviser) in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=24|title=David Nabarro \u2013 David Nabarro's Career History|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n===World Health Organization, 1999\u20132005===\n\nNabarro joined the WHO in January 1999, as project manager of [[Roll Back Malaria (RBM) Partnership|Roll Back Malaria]], then moved to the Office of the DG as executive director in March 2000. In this capacity, he worked with DG [[Gro Harlem Brundtland]] for two years on a variety of issues, including the Commission on Macroeconomics and Health, Health Systems Assessments and the creation of the [[The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria|Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria]].\n\nNabarro transferred to the Sustainable Development and Healthy Environments cluster in 2003 and was appointed representative of the DG for health action in crises in July 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=24|title=David Nabarro - David Nabarro's Career History|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nNabarro was stationed in the [[Canal Hotel]] in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]], when it was [[Canal Hotel Bombing|bombed]] on the afternoon of 19 August 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2003/statment_nabarro/en/|title=WHO {{!}} Senior WHO official, Dr David Nabarro, describes his experience in the UN bombing|website=www.who.int|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> The blast targeted the UN, which had used the hotel as its headquarters in Iraq since 1991.\n\nHe has also coordinated support for health aspects of crisis response operations in [[Darfur]], [[Sudan]], and in countries affected by the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and Tsunami]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/about/who_reform/emergency-capacities/advisory-group/david-nabarro/en/|title=David Nabarro|website=World Health Organization|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== UN System senior coordinator for avian and human influenza (assistant secretary-general), September 2005 \u2013 2014 ===\n\nIn September 2005, Nabarro was seconded from [[World Health Organization|WHO]] and appointed senior UN system coordinator for [[Avian influenza|avian]] and human [[influenza]] by secretary-general of the UN [[Kofi Annan]] to ensure that the UN system makes an effective and coordinated contribution to the global effort to control the epidemic of avian influenza (also known as 'bird flu').<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2005/pr45/en/|title=WHO {{!}} WHO expert to work with the UN system on avian and human influenza|website=www.who.int|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Coordinator of the High-Level Task Force on Global Food Security (HLTF), April 2008 \u2013 April 2014 ===\n\nIn January 2009, Nabarro took on the responsibility of coordinating the UN system's [https://www.un.org/en/issues/food/taskforce/index.shtml High-Level Task Force on Global Food Security (HLTF)].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/issues/food/taskforce/establishing.shtml|title=High Level Task Force on Global Food and Nutrition Security (HLTF)|website=www.un.org|language=EN|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> The HLTF brought together 23 different organizations, funds, programs and other entities from within the UN family, as well as the [[Bretton Woods Institutions]], the [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO), and the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/issues/food/taskforce/updatedmembership.shtml|title=High Level Task Force on Global Food and Nutrition Security (HLTF)|website=www.un.org|language=EN|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> and tasked them with establishing a common strategy for addressing food and nutrition insecurity in a more sustainable, coordinated and comprehensive way. Nabarro left the HLTF coordinator position in 2014 and was succeeded by Giuseppe Fantozzi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/issues/food/taskforce/establishing.shtml|title=High Level Task Force on Global Food and Nutrition Security (HLTF)|website=www.un.org|language=EN|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Coordinator of the Scaling Up Nutrition movement, September 2010 \u2013 September 2015 ===\n\nIn September 2010, Nabarro was appointed coordinator of [http://scalingupnutrition.org/ Scaling Up Nutrition (SUN)].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scalingupnutrition.org/sun-supporters/sun-movement-coordinator/|title=SUN Movement Coordinator|website=scalingupnutrition.org|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> SUN brings together government officials, civil society, the UN, donors, businesses and researchers in a collective effort to improve nutrition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scalingupnutrition.org/about-sun/the-vision-and-principles-of-sun/|title=The vision and principles of SUN|website=scalingupnutrition.org|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Chair of the Advisory Group on Reform of the World Health Organization\u2019s Work in Outbreaks and Emergencies with Health and Humanitarian Consequences., July 2015 \u2013 January 2016 ===\n\nNabarro was responsible for leading a high-level advisory group to guide reform of WHO's response to outbreaks and emergencies, prepare reports based on the group's recommendations and advise on the manner of their implementation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=24|title=David Nabarro - David Nabarro's Career History|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Head of UN's response to cholera in Haiti, summer 2016 \u2013 summer 2017 ===\nIn 2016 Nabarro was tapped to lead the UN's response to Haiti's cholera epidemic. Cholera has killed more than 10,000 Haitians since the disease was introduced by UN peacekeepers in 2010<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/01/world/americas/united-nations-apology-haiti-cholera.html|title=U.N. Apologizes for Role in Haiti\u2019s 2010 Cholera Outbreak|last=Sengupta|first=Somini|date=2016-12-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-06-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>. After UN Secretary General Ban Ki-Moon issued a long overdue apology for the UN's \"role\" in the epidemic, Nabarro oversaw efforts to raise $400 million from UN member states to fund the Secretary General's proposed \"New Approach\" to cholera in Haiti<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/01/world/americas/united-nations-apology-haiti-cholera.html|title=U.N. Apologizes for Role in Haiti\u2019s 2010 Cholera Outbreak|last=Sengupta|first=Somini|date=2016-12-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-06-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>. Nabarro was the second UN appointee to work on the cholera crisis in Haiti. Pedro Modrano Rojas previously served as a senior coordinator for the cholera effort, but left at the end of an 18-month term, stating that he was disappointed by the international community's \"failure to acknowledge the fact that we have in Haiti the largest epidemic in the western hemisphere.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/haiti/article105003956.html|title=British doctor who tackled Ebola now leads fight against cholera in Haiti|access-date=2016-11-23|newspaper=miamiherald}}</ref> Nabarro's efforts were no more successful\u2014as a result of a lack of support from the UN Secretary General and from member states, Nabarro was only been able to raise $2.7 million of the promised $400 million before being replaced by [[Josette Sheeran]]\u2014though Sheeran will face the same obstacles as Nabarro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/haiti/article157148964.html|title=With little money to combat cholera in Haiti, U.N. names new fundraising chief|work=miamiherald|access-date=2017-06-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Special representative of the United Nations Secretary-General for food security and nutrition, November 2009-June 2017 ===\n[[File:Mr. David Nabarro, Special Representative on Food Security and Nutrition, UN High-level Task Force on the Global Food Security Crisis (6139808071).jpg|thumb|Nabarro addresses global food security crisis at Global Commodities Forum, [[United Nations Conference on Trade and Development]]]]\n\nIn November 2009 UN Secretary-General [[Ban Ki-moon]] appointed Nabarro as [[Diplomatic rank|special representative]] on food security and nutrition. As special representative, Nabarro's role is to:\n* Align UN system action on people's food security, livelihood resilience and sustainable agriculture in the face of changing climates\n* Support functioning of the [[Committee on World Food Security]] \n* Oversee UN Secretary-General's [https://www.un.org/zerohunger/ Zero Hunger Challenge].\n\n=== Special adviser to the United Nations Secretary-General on the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development and Climate Change, January 2016\u2013June 2017 ===\n\nIn January 2016, Nabarro was appointed special adviser on the [[Sustainable Development Goals|2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development]] by then UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon.\n\nOne of Nabarro's responsibilities in this role were to lead the UN's response to the cholera epidemic its peacekeepers sparked in Haiti in October 2010 when untreated, infected sewage from a UN base was deposited in the country's main river system. As of August 2016, at least 10,000 people have died and more than 800,000 have been sickened in the ongoing epidemic.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-37126747|title=UN admits role in Haiti's deadly cholera outbreak|date=2016-08-19|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Special envoy of the United Nations Secretary-General on Ebola, August 2014 \u2013 December 2015 ===\n[[File:Dr. David Nabarro, UN Secretary-General's Special Envoy on Ebola speaks at World Organisation for Animal Health.jpg|thumb|David Nabarro speaks at [[World Organization for Animal Health]]]]\n\nIn August 2014, Nabarro was designated as special envoy of the UN Secretary-General on Ebola, with the responsibility for ensuring that the UN system makes an effective and coordinated contribution to the global effort to control the outbreak of Ebola.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ebolaresponse.un.org/special-envoy-ebola|title=Special Envoy on Ebola|date=2014-11-27|newspaper=Global Ebola Response|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> The epidemic is believed to have begun in December 2013 with the death of a 2-year-old boy in a remote area of Guinea, but was not recognized until March 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://who.int/csr/disease/ebola/one-year-report/virus-origin/en/|title=WHO {{!}} Origins of the 2014 Ebola epidemic|website=who.int|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref> For several months the epidemic was spreading. This is something that public health experts in the affected locations, such as [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|Medecins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]] (Doctors Without Borders), claimed was due to a deeply flawed and delayed response by health and government officials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/3753684/ebola-medecins-sans-frontiers-west-africa-world-health-organization-slow-response-cost-lives/|title=Slow Response to Ebola Outbreak 'Cost Thousands of Lives'|last=Regan|first=Helen|website=TIME.com|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview later in 2015, once Ebola had largely been brought under control, Nabarro said that when he started working on Ebola in 2014, he \"was aware that we were in the middle of a disease outbreak of enormous proportions. The number of people getting sick was doubling every week. Facilities were completely overloaded. Communities were in a state of despair.\" He added that the international community had learned important lessons from the epidemic: \"The world is going to be different as a result of this Ebola outbreak, much more confident, much more assured, and much, much more capable to ensure the well-being of its citizens.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/features/2015/ebola-then-now-nabarro/en/|title=Ebola Then and Now - David Nabarro|website=World Health Organization|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Candidate for WHO Director-General September 2016  \u2013 May 2017 ===\n\nAn article co-authored by the UK's [[chief medical officer]], [[Sally Davies (doctor)|Sally Davies]], was published in ''[[The Lancet]]''. It outlined the criteria that the next DG of the WHO must fulfill.\n\nNabarro was one of six candidates put forward by their individual governments to succeed WHO DG [[Margaret Chan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2016/election-process-who-director-general/en/|title=Election process for the new WHO Director-General|website=World Health Organization|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nNabarro outlined his four priorities as follows:\n\n# Alignment with the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs)\n# Transforming the WHO to respond to outbreaks and health emergencies\n# Trusted engagement with Member States\n# Advancing people-centred health policies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davidnabarro.info/index.asp?PageID=29|title=David Nabarro - 4 Priorities|website=davidnabarro.info|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nOn Tuesday 23 May, at the 70th World Health Assembly, Nabarro came second in the race to become the next director general, receiving 50 votes to [[Tedros Adhanom|Dr Tedros Adhanom]]'s 133 in the third and final round of voting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.9and10news.com/story/35495135/the-latest-pakistani-doctor-eliminated-in-who-leader-vote |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-05-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523170003/http://www.9and10news.com/story/35495135/the-latest-pakistani-doctor-eliminated-in-who-leader-vote |archivedate=2017-05-23 }}</ref>\n\n=== Additional positions ===\n* Member of the board of directors, [[Medicines for Malaria Venture]] (MVV), 1999\u20132001<ref>http://www.mmv.org/sites/default/files/uploads/docs/publications/MMV_10th_Anniversary_Book_5.pdf</ref>\n* Member of the WHO Commission on Ending Childhood Obesity (2016), 2013\u20132014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/end-childhood-obesity/about/bios/david-nabarro/en/|title=WHO {{!}} Biographies of the Commissioners|website=www.who.int|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition and awards ==\n*'''World Food Prize 2018''' (dubbed Nobel Prize for Agriculture): Awarded together with [[Lawrence Haddad]] for their individual and complementary global leadership in elevating maternal and child undernutrition to a central issue within the [[food security]] and development dialogue at national and international levels<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfoodprize.org/en/laureates/2018_laureates/|title=2018 Haddad and Nabarro - The World Food Prize - Improving the Quality, Quantity and Availability of Food in the World|last=globalreach.com|first=Global Reach Internet Productions, LLC-Ames, IA-|website=www.worldfoodprize.org|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>. They have been cutting the number of stunted children in the world by 10 million by lobbying governments and donors to improve [[nutrition]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-global-agriculture-nutrition-analysis-idUSKCN1OR03M|title=From obese to starving, nutrition crisis prompts SOS call for new...|date=2018-12-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2018-12-30|language=en}}</ref>.\n*'''Helen Keller Humanitarian Award:''' Awarded for work on positioning [[malnutrition]] within the development dialogue and for ensuring an effective response to [[Ebolavirus|Ebola]], 2015\n* '''Sight and Life Nutrition Leadership Award (together with the Scaling Up Nutrition Movement):''' For work in [[Catalysis|catalysing]] sustainable change in global nutrition, 2012\n* '''Distinguished Service Award from Health Policy Institute, Kansas University of Medicine & Biosciences:''' For outstanding Health Policy Leadership, 2008\n* '''[[CBE]]:''' Awarded for work on international public health, 1992.\n\n==Personal life==\nNabarro has three older children with his former partner, [[Oxfordshire]] GP Susanna Belle Graham-Jones: Thomas (Tom) Adam Nabarro (1984), Oliver Mark Nabarro (1986) and Polly Frances Graham-Jones Nabarro (1988).{{cn|date=February 2017}} David married Gillian Holmes in 2002, in Coppet, near Geneva, and they have two children: Josephine Mari Holmes Nabarro (1997) and Lucas John Nabarro (2000).{{cn|date=February 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://archive.davidnabarro.info/whodg/en/}}\n* {{C-SPAN|David Nabarro}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nabarro, David}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Academics of the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oundle School]]\n[[Category:British public health doctors]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:British officials of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:United Nations operations in Iraq]]\n[[Category:World Health Organization officials]]\n", "name_user": "Sustnabili Thuy", "label": "safe", "comment": "addition that he is now a special envoy on COVID-19", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Nabarro"}
{"title_page": "ZERO\u2014The End of Prostate Cancer", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{cleanup-PR|1=article|date=April 2015}}\n{{COI|date=April 2015}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| logo = ZERO - The End of Prostate Cancer from the front.jpg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| name = ZERO - The End of Prostate Cancer\n| type = [[Nonprofit organization|Healthcare Non-Profit]]\n| services = {{ubl|[[Patient education|Education & Awareness]]|[[Copayment|Patient Financial Assistance]]|\n|[[Cancer research|Cancer Research]]|[[Patient navigators|Patient Navigation]]|[[Advocacy]]}}\n| area_served = [[United States]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1996|07|20}} in [[Washington, DC]]\n| location_city = [[Alexandria, Virginia|Alexandria, VA]]\n| locations = {{ubl|Main office|4 regional chapters}}\n| predecessor = {{ubl|National Prostate Cancer Coalition}}\n| key_people = {{ubl|Jamie Bearse (President & CEO)|Robert Ginyard (Chairman)}}\n| homepage = [https://zerocancer.org zerocancer.org]\n}}\n\n'''ZERO - The End of Prostate Cancer''' is a 501(c)(3) [[non-profit organization|non-profit]] organization dedicated to [[prostate cancer]] education, testing, patient support, research and advocacy.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/59-3400922 | title= ZERO \u2013 The End of Prostate Cancer |website=GuideStar |access-date= August 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe National Prostate Cancer Coalition (NPCC) was founded in 1996 after a task force meeting called by the American Foundation for Urologic Disease (AFUD). The NPCC's stated goal was to unify every major prostate cancer organization in the United States in an effort to, \"bring public awareness to the magnitude of prostate cancer and to ultimately eradicate it.\"<ref>{{cite press release|author=American Foundation for Urologic Disease|title=National Prostate Cancer Coalition based on the National Breast Cancer Coalition model|url=http://www.fathermag.com/9609/prostate_cancer|publisher=Fathermag.com|location=Baltimore, MD|access-date=January 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOriginally modeled after the [[National Breast Cancer Coalition]], NPCC was created to raise funds for prostate cancer research and increasing public awareness of the disease.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Steimle|first1=Sabine|title=NPCC Unifies Prostate Cancer Advocates|journal=JNCI Journal of the National Cancer Institute|date=15 January 1997|volume=89|issue=2|pages=117\u2013118|doi=10.1093/jnci/89.2.117|url=http://jnci.oxfordjournals.org/content/89/2/117.full|accessdate=16 January 2017|doi-access=free}}</ref> Founding members included the American Cancer Society, American Urological Association, and US TOO prostate cancer support network.<ref>Internal Revenue Service certification, June 11, 2003</ref>\n\nThrough the years, the organization's chairmen have included Michael Milken (president, [[Prostate Cancer Foundation]]) and Wesley S. Williams Jr. (former president, Harvard Law School Association). In 2008, the organization changed its name to ZERO\u2014The Project to End Prostate Cancer.<ref>Government of the District of Columbia, Dept. of Consumer and Regulatory Affairs Certificate, July 24, 2008</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>Isaac Itman. \"Prostate Cancer. Did you get screened yet?\" http://minorityhealth.hhs.gov/templates/content.aspx?ID=5178 Office of Minority Health, U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, April 3, 2009. <!--accessed: January 7, 2010-->)</ref> In 2012 the organization changed its name to ZERO - The End of Prostate Cancer.\n\n==Activities==\nZERO has operated The Drive Against Prostate Cancer since 2002.\nThis is a nationwide mobile screening program that provides prostate cancer tests at no charge. Local licensed physicians conduct a two-part early detection procedure, consisting of a Prostate Specific Antigen (PSA) blood test and a physical examination.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Test results are sent to a cancer center for evaluation, and each man receives a notification letter explaining the test results and providing links to information on the web, a toll-free phone number to ZERO, and a contact at the cancer center. Men with abnormal test results receive a second letter urging them to seek medical attention.<ref name=autogenerated1>\"Drive Against Prostate Cancer.\" http://www.thorindustries.com/DAPC THOR Industries. <!--accessed: January 7, 2010-->)</ref>\n\nThe Drive Against Prostate Cancer has traveled to the [[U. S. Capitol]], the [[New York Stock Exchange]], [[Times Square]] and major league ballparks, [[NASCAR]] races, state fairs, and cities and towns across the U.S.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> As of September 2009, more than 100,000 men have received prostate cancer tests at no charge through the Drive Against Prostate Cancer program.<ref>\"Real Stories: Skip Lockwood.\" http://www.cancerresearch.org/RealStories/Public-Education/Prostate-Cancer/Drive.html Cancer Research Institute, November 2009 <!--accessed: November 5, 2009-->)</ref>\n\nSince the introduction of the PSA test in the 1990s as an early detection screening tool for prostate cancer, the prostate cancer death rate has decreased by more than 40 percent.<ref>\"2006 Fact Book\" National Cancer Institute, U.S. Dept. of Health and Human Services, http://obf.cancer.gov/financial/attachments/06Factbk.pdf <!--accessed: February 1, 2010-->)</ref>\nDue to early detection, more than 90 percent of all prostate cancers are found in a localized stage, before spreading to other areas of the body, and the five-year survival rate for these patients approaches 100 percent.<ref>\"Cancer Facts & Figures 2008\" American Cancer Society <!--accessed: February 1, 2010-->)</ref>\n\n[[File:SecyPowell.png|thumb|Retired General [[Colin Powell]]]] \nRetired four-star U.S. Army General [[Colin Powell]], former Secretary of State and also a prostate [[cancer survivor]] since his successful treatment in 2003, encourages all men to get regular prostate check-ups in order to protect their health. \"Men should have regular prostate examinations,\" he said. \"Black men are more susceptible to the disease than others. Regular exams allowed me to deal with this problem early and make a full recovery.\"<ref>\"Gen. Powell Discusses Prostate Cancer on Facebook\" ''U.S. News & World Report'', April 6, 2010. <!--accessed: April 9, 2010-->)</ref>\n\nOther sponsored activities include:\n\n\u2022 The annual [http://www.zeroprostatecancerrun.org ZERO Prostate Cancer Run/Walk], which took place in 42 cities in 2016, included more than 20,000 participants, and raised more than $3 million<ref>{{cite news|title=Zero Prostate Cancer Run/Walk in Bethlehem|url=http://www.wfmz.com/news/lehigh-valley/zero-prostate-cancer-run_walk-in-bethlehem_20160929025711842/99869139|accessdate=17 March 2017|work=WFMZ News|date=27 August 2016}}</ref> for prostate cancer research, education, free testing and direct patient support.\n\n\u2022 An annual \"[http://support.zerocancer.org/site/PageNavigator/AdvocacyCenter/Summit ZERO Prostate Cancer Summit]\" on Capitol Hill, where advocates from across the U.S. meet with elected officials to discuss prostate cancer and early detection testing. ZERO marked its 10th anniversary of this event in 2009. Funding for the two major avenues of prostate cancer research \u2013 The Prostate Cancer Research Program and the National Cancer Institute grants \u2013 has remained virtually flat for nearly a decade.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\n\u2022 Information resource and referral to the public and medical community on prostate cancer research through its website, ZeroCancer.org, and brochures, books, and a weekly electronic newsletter named [http://www.zerocancer.org/archives/aware.html AWARE].\n\n\u2022 An annual \"Grow & Give\" facial hair fundraising campaign in November to raise awareness and money for prostate cancer education programs.<ref>\"ZERO Launches Grow & Give Facial Hair-Growing Campaign\" http://www.pharmiweb.com/pressreleases/pressrel.asp?ROW_ID=103221#.WFAvv6IrKRs#ixzz4SjxFNcuJ <!--accessed: December 12, 2016-->)</ref>\n\n\u2022 Prostate cancer awareness campaigns held each year such as the \"Depend Campaign to End Prostate Cancer\" in collaboration with the Kimberly-Clark Corporation, the \"Know Your Score\" golf tournament held in Pittsburgh, Toronto, Washington D.C. and Myrtle Beach, SC, and the annual \"Prostate Cancer Awareness Month\" proclamation issued in September by the U.S. President.<ref>\"Kimberly-Clark teams up with sports legends to launch The Depend Campaign to End Prostate Cancer.\"\nhttp://www2.prnewswire.com/mnr/depend/39908/ September 17, 2009. <!--accessed: January 25, 2010-->)</ref><ref>\"2009 Know Your Score Raises $65,000.\" http://www.Golfholiday.com/news/area/?aid=98&rss_link=98 September 24, 2009. <!--accessed: October 5,2009-->)</ref><ref>\"National Prostate Cancer Awareness Month, September 2009\" http://www.whitehouse.gov/the_press_office/Presidential-Proclamations-National-Prostate-Cancer-Awareness-Month The White House, Office of the Press Secretary, August 31, 2009. <!--accessed: November 5,2009-->)</ref>\n\n\u2022 Proceeds from the 2009 Great Prostate Cancer Challenge in Baltimore (GPCC) are used to support the American Urological Association Foundation Chesapeake Urology Scholar Fund. ZERO - The Project to End Prostate Cancer, in partnership with Chesapeake Urology Associates, PA donated $45,000 to the American Urological Association Foundation Chesapeake Urology Research Fund to award grants to prostate cancer research. To date, the GPCC race has contributed nearly $300,000 in scholarship monies to the AUA Foundation Chesapeake Urology Research Fund and has a goal of raising $750,000 in total.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} The AUA Foundation is the world's leading non-profit urological health organization{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} and the official foundation of the American Urological Association. The AUA Foundation's mission is to promote health, provide hope and promise a future free of urological disease.\n\n==Media==\nZERO's spokespersons in past years have included [[Bob Dole]], [[Dr. Joyce Brothers]], [[Lou Rawls]], [[Ken Griffey, Sr.]], [[Len Dawson]], [[Jesse Jackson, Jr.|Jesse Jackson Jr.]] and [[Jim Boeheim]].\n<ref>''Los Angeles Sentinel.'' September 6, 2001. \"Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr. urges men: talk to MD about prostate cancer.\"</ref><ref>Holly C. Corbett, \"Hall of fame coach beats cancer.\" http://www.Mensfitness.com/sports_and_recreation/athletes/177 September 2009. <!--accessed: January 7, 2010-->)</ref>\nThe organization's work has been recognized in publications such as ''[[USA Today]]'', the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', the ''[[Washington Post]]'', the ''[[Los Angeles Sentinel]]'', and the ''[[New York Daily News]]''.<ref>''USA Today.'' October 14, 2002. Mike Falcon and Stephen A Shoop. \"Giuliani beats prostate cancer.\" https://www.usatoday.com/news/health/spotlighthealth/2002-10-14-giuliani_x.htm <!--accessed: January 8, 2010-->)</ref><ref>''Chicago Tribune.'' Sept. 29, 2002. Ross Werland. \"Check the oil and the prostate.\"</ref><ref>''New York Daily News.'' June 21, 2002. \"Getting PSA test is worth a day off.\"</ref>\n\nZERO supported other cancer organizations in 2009 in launching the \"Stand Up to Cancer\" awareness campaign featuring tennis pro [[John McEnroe]], who encouraged men aged 40 and older to get an annual prostate cancer check-up.<ref>\"Tennis legend John McEnroe tells men to 'get serious' about prostate cancer,\" http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=5268869n CBS News. August 27, 2009. <!--accessed: January 8, 2010-->)</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.zerocancer.org Official site]\n* [http://www.aua.org American Urological Association]\n* [http://www.nccn.org National Comprehensive Cancer Network=k]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zero-The End of Prostate Cancer}}\n[[Category:Cancer fundraisers|Fundraising]]\n[[Category:Urology organizations]]\n[[Category:Cancer charities in the United States]]\n[[Category:Charities based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Prostate cancer]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1996]]\n[[Category:1996 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organizations based in Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{cleanup-PR|1=article|date=April 2015}}\n{{COI|date=April 2015}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| logo = ZERO - The End of Prostate Cancer from the front.jpg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| name = ZERO - The End of Prostate Cancer\n| type = [[Nonprofit organization|Healthcare Non-Profit]]\n| services = {{ubl|[[Patient education|Education & Awareness]]|[[Copayment|Patient Financial Assistance]]|\n|[[Cancer research|Cancer Research]]|[[Patient navigators|Patient Navigation]]|[[Advocacy]]}}\n| area_served = [[United States]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1996|07|20}} in [[Washington, DC]]\n| location_city = [[Alexandria, Virginia|Alexandria, VA]]\n| locations = {{ubl|Main office|4 regional chapters}}\n| predecessor = {{ubl|National Prostate Cancer Coalition}}\n| key_people = {{ubl|Jamie Bearse (President & CEO)|Quentin \"Skip\" Lockwood (Chairman)}}\n| homepage = [https://zerocancer.org zerocancer.org]\n}}\n\n'''ZERO - The End of Prostate Cancer''' is a 501(c)(3) [[non-profit organization|non-profit]] organization dedicated to [[prostate cancer]] education, testing, patient support, research and advocacy.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/59-3400922 | title= ZERO \u2013 The End of Prostate Cancer |website=GuideStar |access-date= August 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe National Prostate Cancer Coalition (NPCC) was founded in 1996 after a task force meeting called by the American Foundation for Urologic Disease (AFUD). The NPCC's stated goal was to unify every major prostate cancer organization in the United States in an effort to, \"bring public awareness to the magnitude of prostate cancer and to ultimately eradicate it.\"<ref>{{cite press release|author=American Foundation for Urologic Disease|title=National Prostate Cancer Coalition based on the National Breast Cancer Coalition model|url=http://www.fathermag.com/9609/prostate_cancer|publisher=Fathermag.com|location=Baltimore, MD|access-date=January 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOriginally modeled after the [[National Breast Cancer Coalition]], NPCC was created to raise funds for prostate cancer research and increasing public awareness of the disease.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Steimle|first1=Sabine|title=NPCC Unifies Prostate Cancer Advocates|journal=JNCI Journal of the National Cancer Institute|date=15 January 1997|volume=89|issue=2|pages=117\u2013118|doi=10.1093/jnci/89.2.117|url=http://jnci.oxfordjournals.org/content/89/2/117.full|accessdate=16 January 2017|doi-access=free}}</ref> Founding members included the American Cancer Society, American Urological Association, and US TOO prostate cancer support network.<ref>Internal Revenue Service certification, June 11, 2003</ref>\n\nThrough the years, the organization's chairmen have included Michael Milken (president, [[Prostate Cancer Foundation]]) and Wesley S. Williams Jr. (former president, Harvard Law School Association). In 2008, the organization changed its name to ZERO\u2014The Project to End Prostate Cancer.<ref>Government of the District of Columbia, Dept. of Consumer and Regulatory Affairs Certificate, July 24, 2008</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>Isaac Itman. \"Prostate Cancer. Did you get screened yet?\" http://minorityhealth.hhs.gov/templates/content.aspx?ID=5178 Office of Minority Health, U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, April 3, 2009. <!--accessed: January 7, 2010-->)</ref> In 2012 the organization changed its name to ZERO - The End of Prostate Cancer.\n\n==Activities==\nZERO has operated The Drive Against Prostate Cancer since 2002.\nThis is a nationwide mobile screening program that provides prostate cancer tests at no charge. Local licensed physicians conduct a two-part early detection procedure, consisting of a Prostate Specific Antigen (PSA) blood test and a physical examination.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Test results are sent to a cancer center for evaluation, and each man receives a notification letter explaining the test results and providing links to information on the web, a toll-free phone number to ZERO, and a contact at the cancer center. Men with abnormal test results receive a second letter urging them to seek medical attention.<ref name=autogenerated1>\"Drive Against Prostate Cancer.\" http://www.thorindustries.com/DAPC THOR Industries. <!--accessed: January 7, 2010-->)</ref>\n\nThe Drive Against Prostate Cancer has traveled to the [[U. S. Capitol]], the [[New York Stock Exchange]], [[Times Square]] and major league ballparks, [[NASCAR]] races, state fairs, and cities and towns across the U.S.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> As of September 2009, more than 100,000 men have received prostate cancer tests at no charge through the Drive Against Prostate Cancer program.<ref>\"Real Stories: Skip Lockwood.\" http://www.cancerresearch.org/RealStories/Public-Education/Prostate-Cancer/Drive.html Cancer Research Institute, November 2009 <!--accessed: November 5, 2009-->)</ref>\n\nSince the introduction of the PSA test in the 1990s as an early detection screening tool for prostate cancer, the prostate cancer death rate has decreased by more than 40 percent.<ref>\"2006 Fact Book\" National Cancer Institute, U.S. Dept. of Health and Human Services, http://obf.cancer.gov/financial/attachments/06Factbk.pdf <!--accessed: February 1, 2010-->)</ref>\nDue to early detection, more than 90 percent of all prostate cancers are found in a localized stage, before spreading to other areas of the body, and the five-year survival rate for these patients approaches 100 percent.<ref>\"Cancer Facts & Figures 2008\" American Cancer Society <!--accessed: February 1, 2010-->)</ref>\n\n[[File:SecyPowell.png|thumb|Retired General [[Colin Powell]]]] \nRetired four-star U.S. Army General [[Colin Powell]], former Secretary of State and also a prostate [[cancer survivor]] since his successful treatment in 2003, encourages all men to get regular prostate check-ups in order to protect their health. \"Men should have regular prostate examinations,\" he said. \"Black men are more susceptible to the disease than others. Regular exams allowed me to deal with this problem early and make a full recovery.\"<ref>\"Gen. Powell Discusses Prostate Cancer on Facebook\" ''U.S. News & World Report'', April 6, 2010. <!--accessed: April 9, 2010-->)</ref>\n\nOther sponsored activities include:\n\n\u2022 The annual [http://www.zeroprostatecancerrun.org ZERO Prostate Cancer Run/Walk], which took place in 42 cities in 2016, included more than 20,000 participants, and raised more than $3 million<ref>{{cite news|title=Zero Prostate Cancer Run/Walk in Bethlehem|url=http://www.wfmz.com/news/lehigh-valley/zero-prostate-cancer-run_walk-in-bethlehem_20160929025711842/99869139|accessdate=17 March 2017|work=WFMZ News|date=27 August 2016}}</ref> for prostate cancer research, education, free testing and direct patient support.\n\n\u2022 An annual \"[http://support.zerocancer.org/site/PageNavigator/AdvocacyCenter/Summit ZERO Prostate Cancer Summit]\" on Capitol Hill, where advocates from across the U.S. meet with elected officials to discuss prostate cancer and early detection testing. ZERO marked its 10th anniversary of this event in 2009. Funding for the two major avenues of prostate cancer research \u2013 The Prostate Cancer Research Program and the National Cancer Institute grants \u2013 has remained virtually flat for nearly a decade.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\n\u2022 Information resource and referral to the public and medical community on prostate cancer research through its website, ZeroCancer.org, and brochures, books, and a weekly electronic newsletter named [http://www.zerocancer.org/archives/aware.html AWARE].\n\n\u2022 An annual \"Grow & Give\" facial hair fundraising campaign in November to raise awareness and money for prostate cancer education programs.<ref>\"ZERO Launches Grow & Give Facial Hair-Growing Campaign\" http://www.pharmiweb.com/pressreleases/pressrel.asp?ROW_ID=103221#.WFAvv6IrKRs#ixzz4SjxFNcuJ <!--accessed: December 12, 2016-->)</ref>\n\n\u2022 Prostate cancer awareness campaigns held each year such as the \"Depend Campaign to End Prostate Cancer\" in collaboration with the Kimberly-Clark Corporation, the \"Know Your Score\" golf tournament held in Pittsburgh, Toronto, Washington D.C. and Myrtle Beach, SC, and the annual \"Prostate Cancer Awareness Month\" proclamation issued in September by the U.S. President.<ref>\"Kimberly-Clark teams up with sports legends to launch The Depend Campaign to End Prostate Cancer.\"\nhttp://www2.prnewswire.com/mnr/depend/39908/ September 17, 2009. <!--accessed: January 25, 2010-->)</ref><ref>\"2009 Know Your Score Raises $65,000.\" http://www.Golfholiday.com/news/area/?aid=98&rss_link=98 September 24, 2009. <!--accessed: October 5,2009-->)</ref><ref>\"National Prostate Cancer Awareness Month, September 2009\" http://www.whitehouse.gov/the_press_office/Presidential-Proclamations-National-Prostate-Cancer-Awareness-Month The White House, Office of the Press Secretary, August 31, 2009. <!--accessed: November 5,2009-->)</ref>\n\n\u2022 Proceeds from the 2009 Great Prostate Cancer Challenge in Baltimore (GPCC) are used to support the American Urological Association Foundation Chesapeake Urology Scholar Fund. ZERO - The Project to End Prostate Cancer, in partnership with Chesapeake Urology Associates, PA donated $45,000 to the American Urological Association Foundation Chesapeake Urology Research Fund to award grants to prostate cancer research. To date, the GPCC race has contributed nearly $300,000 in scholarship monies to the AUA Foundation Chesapeake Urology Research Fund and has a goal of raising $750,000 in total.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} The AUA Foundation is the world's leading non-profit urological health organization{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} and the official foundation of the American Urological Association. The AUA Foundation's mission is to promote health, provide hope and promise a future free of urological disease.\n\n==Media==\nZERO's spokespersons in past years have included [[Bob Dole]], [[Dr. Joyce Brothers]], [[Lou Rawls]], [[Ken Griffey, Sr.]], [[Len Dawson]], [[Jesse Jackson, Jr.|Jesse Jackson Jr.]] and [[Jim Boeheim]].\n<ref>''Los Angeles Sentinel.'' September 6, 2001. \"Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr. urges men: talk to MD about prostate cancer.\"</ref><ref>Holly C. Corbett, \"Hall of fame coach beats cancer.\" http://www.Mensfitness.com/sports_and_recreation/athletes/177 September 2009. <!--accessed: January 7, 2010-->)</ref>\nThe organization's work has been recognized in publications such as ''[[USA Today]]'', the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', the ''[[Washington Post]]'', the ''[[Los Angeles Sentinel]]'', and the ''[[New York Daily News]]''.<ref>''USA Today.'' October 14, 2002. Mike Falcon and Stephen A Shoop. \"Giuliani beats prostate cancer.\" https://www.usatoday.com/news/health/spotlighthealth/2002-10-14-giuliani_x.htm <!--accessed: January 8, 2010-->)</ref><ref>''Chicago Tribune.'' Sept. 29, 2002. Ross Werland. \"Check the oil and the prostate.\"</ref><ref>''New York Daily News.'' June 21, 2002. \"Getting PSA test is worth a day off.\"</ref>\n\nZERO supported other cancer organizations in 2009 in launching the \"Stand Up to Cancer\" awareness campaign featuring tennis pro [[John McEnroe]], who encouraged men aged 40 and older to get an annual prostate cancer check-up.<ref>\"Tennis legend John McEnroe tells men to 'get serious' about prostate cancer,\" http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=5268869n CBS News. August 27, 2009. <!--accessed: January 8, 2010-->)</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.zerocancer.org Official site]\n* [http://www.aua.org American Urological Association]\n* [http://www.nccn.org National Comprehensive Cancer Network=k]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zero-The End of Prostate Cancer}}\n[[Category:Cancer fundraisers|Fundraising]]\n[[Category:Urology organizations]]\n[[Category:Cancer charities in the United States]]\n[[Category:Charities based in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Prostate cancer]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1996]]\n[[Category:1996 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organizations based in Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "SuperJerms", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated board of directors chairman", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZERO%E2%80%94The_End_of_Prostate_Cancer"}
{"title_page": "2020 United States Senate election in Alabama", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2020 United States Senate election in Alabama\n| country            = Alabama\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2017 United States Senate special election in Alabama\n| previous_year      = 2017 (special)\n| next_election      = 2026 United States Senate election in Alabama\n| next_year          = 2026\n| election_date      = November 3, 2020\n| image1             = [[File:Senator Doug Jones official photo (cropped 2).jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee1           = [[Doug Jones (politician)|Doug Jones]]\n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        = \n| image2             = [[File:No image.svg|x110px]]\n| nominee2           = TBD\n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        = \n| map_image          = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = County results\n| title              = U.S. Senator\n| before_election    = [[Doug Jones (politician)|Doug Jones]]\n| before_party       = Democratic Party (United States)\n| after_election     = \n| after_party        = \n}}\n{{ElectionsAL}}\n\nThe '''2020 United States Senate election in Alabama''' will be held on November 3, 2020, to elect a member of the [[United States Senate]] to represent the [[Alabama|State of Alabama]], concurrently with the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 U.S. presidential election]], as well as [[2020 United States Senate elections|other elections]] to the United States Senate in other states, [[2020 United States House of Representatives elections|elections]] to the [[United States House of Representatives]], and various [[2020 United States elections#State elections|state]] and [[2020 United States elections#Local elections|local elections]].\n\nIncumbent [[Doug Jones (politician)|Doug Jones]], first elected in a [[2017 United States Senate special election in Alabama|2017 special election]], will run for a full term. Jones is one of two Democratic U.S. senators facing reelection in 2020 in a state President [[Donald Trump]] carried in [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]], the other being [[Gary Peters]] from [[Michigan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/campaigns/trump-won-michigan-2016-matter-gary-peters-2020|title=Trump won Michigan in 2016. Does that matter for Gary Peters in 2020?|author=Simone Path\u00e9|date=January 31, 2019|work=[[Roll Call]]}}</ref>\n\n==Democratic primary==\nThe candidate filing deadline was November 8, 2019. Doug Jones is running unopposed.<ref>{{cite web |title=United States Senate election in Alabama, 2020 (March 3 Democratic primary) |url=https://ballotpedia.org/United_States_Senate_election_in_Alabama,_2020_(March_3_Democratic_primary) |website=ballotpedia.org |accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Candidates file 2020 papers as Alabama qualifying window closes |url=https://www.wsfa.com/2019/11/08/candidates-file-papers-alabama-qualifying-window-closes/ |accessdate=January 13, 2020 |work=WSFA 12 News |date=November 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n*[[Doug Jones (politician)|Doug Jones]], incumbent U.S. Senator<ref>{{cite tweet|last=Cohen|first=Zach|user=Zachary_Cohen|number=1062472956608212992|date=November 13, 2018|title=#ALsen Doug Jones (D) confirms he\u2019ll seek reelection in 2020. \u201cAlready off and running.\u201d|accessdate=November 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Declined====\n*[[John Rogers (Alabama politician)|John Rogers]], state representative<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ross|first1=Sean|title=State Rep. John Rogers not running for U.S. Senate, says Jones showing \u2018conservatism\u2019 but not racist|url=https://yellowhammernews.com/state-rep-john-rogers-not-running-for-u-s-senate-says-jones-showing-conservatism-but-not-racist/|publisher=Yellowhammer News|date=August 21, 2019|accessdate=August 22, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Randall Woodfin]], [[List of mayors of Birmingham, Alabama|mayor of Birmingham]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2017/12/alabama_senate_race_who_could.html|title=Alabama Senate race: Who could challenge Doug Jones in 2020?|work=AL.com|access-date=December 16, 2017|last1=Gore|first1=Leada|date=December 14, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Endorsements===\n{{Endorsements box\n|title=Doug Jones\n|list=\n; U.S. Senators\n* [[Tammy Baldwin]], U.S. Senator (D-WI)<ref name=\"Donations\">Baldwin, Blumenthal, Brown, Coons, Cortez Masto, Menendez, and Merkley sent out emails to supporters soliciting donations to Jones.</ref>\n* [[Richard Blumenthal]], U.S. Senator (D-CT)<ref name=\"Donations\"/>\n* [[Sherrod Brown]], U.S. Senator (D-OH)<ref name=\"Donations\"/>\n* [[Chris Coons]], U.S. Senator (D-DE)<ref name=\"Donations\"/>\n* [[Catherine Cortez Masto]], U.S. Senator (D-NV)<ref name=\"Donations\"/>\n* [[Dick Durbin]], U.S. Senator (D-IL) and [[Senate Minority Whip]]<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=DickDurbin|number=1192939990923087872|title=Deal me in, @ChrisMurphyCT & @brianschatz. We can\u2019t let Jeff Sessions or Roy Moore win this Senate seat. Chip in now to support @DougJones: http://bit.ly/2Q6Y4Yp\u00a0https://twitter.com/ChrisMurphyCT/status/1192627151964659713\u00a0\u2026|first=Dick|last=Durbin|date=November 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Kamala Harris]], U.S. Senator (D-CA) and former 2020 presidential candidate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yellowhammernews.com/californias-kamala-harris-raising-money-for-doug-jones-based-on-sessions-opposition/|title=California's Kamala Harris raising money for Doug Jones based on Sessions opposition|date=November 7, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Amy Klobuchar]], U.S. Senator (D-MN) and former 2020 presidential candidate<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/449640-klobuchar-fundraises-for-doug-jones-following-roy-moores-senate-run|title=Klobuchar fundraises for Doug Jones following Roy Moore Senate run|work=The Hill|date=June 20, 2019|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Joe Manchin]], U.S. Senator (D-WV)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/23/doug-jones-democrat-alabama-trump-055034|title=Doug Jones is the Senate's most vulnerable incumbent. But he doesn't seem to care.|last=Arkin|first=James|work=Politico|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=November 7, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Bob Menendez]], U.S. Senator (D-NJ)<ref name=\"Donations\"/>\n* [[Jeff Merkley]], U.S. Senator (D-OR)<ref name=\"Donations\"/>\n* [[Chris Murphy]], U.S. Senator (D-CT)\n* [[Brian Schatz]], U.S. Senator (D-HI)<ref>{{cite tweet|user=brianschatz|number=1192514166336217094|date=November 7, 2019|accessdate=November 7, 2019|title=Doug Jones prosecuted the racist Birmingham bomber and is a great Senator. His opponent will be either Jeff Sessions or Roy Moore and if that doesn\u2019t make you want to send money I don\u2019t know what to tell you. But seriously please give. Thanks.}}</ref>\n; U.S. Representative\n* [[Terri Sewell]], (D-AL)<ref name=\"al.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/09/doug-jones-kicks-off-2020-campaign-in-birmingham.html|title=Doug Jones kicks off 2020 campaign in Birmingham|first=Anna Claire|last=Vollers|date=September 8, 2019|website=al}}</ref>\n; Local officials \n* [[Stacey Abrams]], [[2018 Georgia gubernatorial election|2018]] Democratic nominee for Governor of Georgia, former Minority Leader of the [[Georgia House of Representatives]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/sep/2/stacey-abrams-passes-on-2020-run-turns-focus-to-vo/|title=Stacey Abrams passes on 2020 run, turns focus to voter access with Fair Fight|author=James Varney|work=The Washington Times}}</ref>\n*[[Randall Woodfin]], [[List of mayors of Birmingham, Alabama|Mayor of Birmingham]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n; Individuals\n* [[Michael O'Neill (actor)|Michael O'Neill]], actor<r